<p><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p>July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">and was mortified to observe the imperious manner in which these poor innocent Strangers were treated by the Vagabonds of the Villages during their Stay among them<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  In course of our late jaunt we had an offer of a very handsome Slave Girl for a gun and a hundred rounds of ammunition.  But the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Gros Ventres</span> would not allow us to purchase her Saying that she would answer for themselves<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Crow Indians and the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Gros Ventres</span> speak almost the same language and there is a great resemblance in many other respects which induces a beleif that they were originally the same nation<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I am told they are given to unnatural connexions and satisfy their inordinate desires in an extra<span class="AddHand-author">or</span>dinary manner.  We have also Seen a few <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Flat heads</span> in the Villages.  These differ in Language and resemblance from their neighbours the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Crow Indians</span>.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The weather was very hot and the quantity of water we drank was astonishing<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  At first we disliked the looks and could scarcly <span class="DelHand-author"><span class="AddHand-editors">[...ld]</span></span> taste the water of the Missisouri &#8212; being strongly impregnated with Clay<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  But the continual use the inhabitants make of it without any bad effect</p>
<p style="text-align:right;"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">proves</span></p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[75]</span></p>

